stylometry: The factors and trade off associated with deciding when to place an order include lead time, different costs associated with ordering, and demand.  Lead time is the amount of time it takes for the products to be delivered after they are ordered.  If a company orders their products on tuesday and they do not receive them to saturday, the lead time is 4 days.  When they place this order they must make sure they have enough inventory on hand to handle the demand expected for four days, until the products arrive.  Sometimes lead times are miscalculated and then the company runs into problems.  There are different variables in costs when placing orders.  Sometimes there are fixed costs for every order you place or there might just be an annual fixed cost associated with the stuff you are ordering.  You has a company have to decide what makes more sense and whats fixed costs are you being charged.  This plays a large role in when you order.  If they charge on number you might order more frequently and in smaller quantities or bulk if they give you a better price.  If they fixed costs are based on the specific order you are going to want to make big orders so you dont have to keep ordering and accumulating a higher fixed cost.  When you take into consideration the first two things talked about, now you must take into consideration demand. What a company does in the first two steps is largely affected by demand.  Demand will dictate when to order things based on how fast they are moving off of the shelves and does it make more sense to order more often or in larger or smaller quantities.
